\begin_layout Standard
Although it has never been monolithic and has gone through several identifiable
 phases, until around 1990 it always had enough coherence for commentators
 to characterize each phase by some combination of its main theoretical
 and methodological approach: ideographic regional studies before World
 War II, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

spatial science
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 relying on neoclassical economics and quantitative (mainly statistical)
 methods between 1950 and 1970; and, during the seventies and eighties,
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

structuralist
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (Marxian) political economy combining multiple research methods with historical
 materialism, especially Marxist political economy, to analyze deep-seated,
 large-scale sociospatial economic change 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "scott07economic,barnes2010nothing"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Here I follow 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citeauthor
key "scott07economic"

\end_inset

's practice of parenthesizing this phase's Marxist leanings.
 This is not because I am adverse to using the term, as I suspect neither
 is Scott, but because many scholars working in this vein at the time eschewed
 the term themselves.
 This was especially true in the United States, where a long history of
 anti-communism and the Cold War made (and makes) anything labeled 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Marxist
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 unlikely to get a hearing in most academia and policy circles.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 But in the late eighties critics increasingly attacked the latter approach.
 Significantly, these critics were usually sympathetic in that they shared
 political economy's inclination to reject spatial sciences technocratic
 impulse in favor of a broader project of human liberation, and their criticisms
 generally maintained the approach was incomplete and too restrictive rather
 than incorrect.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Incomplete by ignoring or downplaying class conflict, gender, human subjectivity
 and agency, non-capitalist elements in existing economies, and so on.
 Of course, an approach that is incomplete very likely will be unable to
 explain empirical situations on its own, and the causal efficacy of what
 it claims to know will depend on elements the approach omits.
 So in the sense that the structural logic was (mis)applied to certain situation
s, the approach was incorrect.
 Besides this, perhaps the main substantive criticism of the approach per
 se is that it was insufficiently open.
 See 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "490 - 491."
key "scott07economic"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These criticisms were linked to new research initiatives focusing on what
 was missing, and this introduced a centrifugal dynamic to the field.
 Throughout the 1990s, fragmentation came to characterize the field, as
 it ventured into various approaches: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the locality project [locality studies], critical realism, feminism, regulationi
sm, institutionalism, culture, post-modernism, post-structuralism, relationalism
, 'General Darwinism,' and even a reconstructed (or in some critics' eyes
 unreconstructed) spatial science
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
after "201"
key "barnes2010nothing"

\end_inset

.
 Additionally, the accelerating pace and geographic unevenness of change
 in the global economy motivated a rapidly changing set of research concerns:
 corporate geography, socio-spatial divisions of labor, spatial demographics,
 Japanization, flexible specialization, technology districts, the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

creative class,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 cultural production, networks, etc.
 Combined with the uneven development of geography in academia, the field's
 inherent fast-moving character, and its traditions of tolerance for diversity,
 this caused economic geography to come to resemble a desert island inhabited
 by a collection of amicable, yet inbred and disconnected intellectual tribes
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "peck2012economic"

\end_inset

.
 The field became rather chaotic and unfocused, with frequent disruptions
 by faddish 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

turns
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (cultural, relational, evolutionary, etc.).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this environment, there is little chance of developing a substantial
 research program on large-scale economic processes.
 Even if a subset of scholars sought to develop a strong research program
 by focusing on a set of questions over an extended period of time, the
 disruptions caused by the latest fads would make this very difficult.
 Moreover, most 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

tribes
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 are interested in the local, the micro, and the meso.
 As Jamie 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "peck2016macroeconomic"

\end_inset

 puts it, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

contemporary economic geography arguably finds most of its questions amid
 the churn and chop of capitalist restructuring, but much less attention
 is being paid to the structural dynamics of that churn and chop.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Both 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "taylor2012islandlife"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
